div2.p:
Of the four triads, the first is taken up with the introduction, and
                                the preparation of the myth; the second and third contain the myth;
                                the fourth connects the myth with the conclusion.

div3.p:
θαλπνότερον . . .
                                    φαεννόν: P. delights in double epithets, vv. 10, 59;
                                        O. 2.60. 90.

θῆκε: Sc. Ἡρακλῆς. Change of subject is very
                                    common in Greek, e. g. O. 9.50;
                                        P. 4.25. 251. See also O. 1.89.

κρανααῖς ἐν
                                    Ἀθάναις: So O. 13.38;
                                        N. 8.11.

τελέσαις: Participle;
                                        ἀρέομαι must be
                                recalled.

φέρων: Figuratively,
                                    as elsewhere μόλον, P. 3.68; ἔβαν, N. 4.74;
                                    6, 65. Compare v. 68.

ὀρσοτρίαιναν:
                                    Poseidon is so called, O. 8.48;
                                        N. 4.86.

χρυσοχαῖτα: Vocative
                                    used as nominative. Elsewhere χρυσοκόμας, O. 6.41;
                                    7, 32.

καὶ μάν: It is hard
                                    to believe Tityos dead with this gigantic youth before our eyes;
                                    hence the oath by way of confirmation, as v. 87.

ματρυιᾶς:
                                    Ino-Leukothea, acc. to the common form of the familiar legend;
                                    acc. to P., Demodike (Schol.).

εὐρυβία: A title in
                                    the Poseidon family, O. 6.58;
                                        P. 2.12.

τέχναις: By putting
                                    him to sleep. Pl., as O. 9.56;
                                        P. 3.11.
